# CampuGrid Phase 1 Verification

Phase 1 (Server Core & Infrastructure) has been successfully implemented and tested.

The reason you received a `404 Not Found` when visiting `http://localhost:8000/` is because the API endpoints are mounted under `/api/v1` and there is no route bound to the root URL.

## How to Test

FastAPI automatically generates an interactive documentation site for your API.

### 1. Open the Interactive Swagger UI
Open your browser and navigate to the interactive API docs:
**[http://localhost:8000/docs](http://localhost:8000/docs)**

> [!TIP]
> This is a fully interactive interface. You can click on any endpoint, click **"Try it out"**, fill in the JSON payload, and hit **"Execute"** right from the browser!

### 2. Verify Server Health
In the Swagger UI, navigate to the `/health` endpoint and execute it.
You should see output similar to this, confirming the backend is communicating with Docker Compose services:
```json
{
  "status": "ok",
  "services": {
    "database": "connected",
    "redis": "connected",
    "minio": "connected"
  }
}
```

### 3. Test User Registration
1. In the `/docs` UI, find `POST /api/v1/auth/register`.
2. Click **Try it out**.
3. Use the following payload:
```json
{
  "email": "student@university.edu",
  "name": "Samito",
  "password": "securepassword123",
  "role": "both"
}
```
4. Click **Execute**. You will receive a `201 Created` response containing a JWT `access_token` and your user profile.

### 4. Authorize for Protected Endpoints
1. Copy the `access_token` value you received from the registration step.
2. Scroll to the top of the `/docs` page and click the green **Authorize** padlock button.
3. Paste the token into the Value field and click Authorize.
4. You can now execute protected endpoints (like the `/api/v1/auth/me` or `/api/v1/nodes/me`).

### 5. Check Pricing Estimates
Test the dynamic GPU pricing logic by trying out the `GET /api/v1/jobs/estimate/price` endpoint. Set `gpu_tier` to `RTX 4090` and `estimated_hours` to `5` to see the live competitor cost comparisons!

## What was Accomplished in Phase 1?

- **Infrastructure Started**: Postgres (database), Redis (pub/sub & queue), MinIO (object storage S3 alternative) are all running via Docker Compose.
- **SQLAlchemy Models**: Fully structured user tables, node hardware tracking, compute jobs, chunks, billing records, and container images.
- **Alembic Migrations**: The database schemas were autogenerated into migrations and applied reliably to the database container.
- **MinIO integration**: Object storage buckets for job inputs/outputs were auto-created on startup.
- **WebSocket Manager**: Global singleton logic handles realtime node heartbeats and client progress streams.
- **REST Router**: Auth, Jobs, Nodes, and Billing endpoints were wired securely with our JWT mechanism and native `bcrypt` password hashing.

> [!NOTE]
> Are you ready to proceed to Phase 3? In **Phase 3**, we will build out the final fault-tolerance layers (Celery Beat Watchdog to detect node failures) and the dynamic Gemini Dockerfile Verifier & Generator to adapt missing packages dynamically.

